The only definite obstacles to generating the string would be

• a terminal that is not produced by any non‑terminal, or  
• a place where the grammar forces a fixed terminal that disagrees with the
string.

Every terminal in the string does appear in (at least) one lexical rule:

t23  →  NT11  
t6   →  NT4  
t11  →  NT8, NT13, NT19, NT7  
t33  →  NT41, NT5, NT38  
t28  →  NT2, NT18, NT38, NT41  
t10  →  NT29, NT10, NT31  
t9   →  NT22  
t29  →  NT37, NT18  
t21  →  NT13  
t14  →  NT36  
t7   →  NT35, NT33  
t5   →  NT7, NT35  
t32  →  NT0  
t17  →  NT40, NT18  
t31  →  NT20  
t2   →  NT21  
t12  →  NT30, NT2  
t4   →  NT15, NT12, NT39, NT2  
t22  →  NT3, NT4, NT23  
t8   →  NT21

Hence there is no lexical gap.

Next, there are no productions that force a particular terminal at a fixed
position—the grammar is entirely in Chomsky normal form (all non‑lexical
rules are binary), so any sequence of terminals can in principle be produced
as long as the required non‑terminals can be arranged in a binary tree whose
leaves have the right lexical labels.  Because the grammar is highly
recursive (e.g. NT22 → NT42 NT41, NT42 → NT38 NT1, NT1 → NT9 NT3, …) every
lexical non‑terminal above appears in many binary rules, and each of those
non‑terminals can be positioned arbitrarily within larger derivations by
these recursive rules.  There is therefore no structural constraint that
blocks any particular ordering of the terminals.

Since (1) every token in the given string is derivable,
and (2) the grammar’s binary rules allow those tokens to be combined in any
order and in any length via the abundant recursive productions,

the grammar can indeed generate the entire 32‑token string.

Yes
